  "edge_hypothesis": "KAMA (Kaufman Adaptive Moving Average) speeds up in trends and slows down in noise. SMA_50 moves at a constant rate regardless of market conditions. When KAMA crosses above/below SMA_50, it reveals a speed differential — the adaptive average has begun moving faster than the fixed average, meaning the market is transitioning from noise to directional commitment. This is a pure price-structure transition signal with NO oscillator component. KAMA has only been tested with oscillators (KAMA+Stoch PF=1.857 ACCEPT, KAMA+RSI in queue). The speed-differential crossover is a fundamentally different signal type — it measures the market's acceleration relative to its average pace, not overbought/oversold conditions. Single-condition entry (max simplicity) tests whether KAMA's adaptive nature alone provides sufficient edge without confirmation.",
